GOAL: Improve, optimize and extend HVM's AOT compiler. 
======================================================

HVM has an AOT compiler (./clang/aot/), that converts user-defined functions
into faster, native C procedures. It works is by *emulating* HVM's interpreter
against a statically known top-level definition; technically, acting as a
*partial application* of the interpreter against the compiled function. For
example, consider the mul2 definition:

mul2 = λ{0:0;1+:λp.mul2(p-1)}
main = mul2(123)

On interpreted mode, 'mul2(123)' *expands* mul2 lazily via ALO (allocation) nodes,
allowing the program above to unfold as:

<λ{0:0;1+:λp.mul2(p-1)}>(123)
<λp.mul2(p-1)>(123)
λp.<mul2(p-1)>(123)
<mul2(p-1)|p←123>
<mul2(p-1)|p←123>
<mul2|p←123>(<p-1|p←123>)
mul2(123-1)

Where <p> is an ALO node pointing to a static, immutable top-level definition
Term AST. This somewhat efficient, since ALO expands lazily, and we never have
to allocate unreached branches. Yet, it is still wasteful, because we *know* the
shape of mul2 statically, so, reading it and allocating (ALO) intermediate
sub-expressions over and over is not efficient. Instead, we could have just
compiled it to a native C function that doesn't allocate anything at all:

Term mul2() {
  // perform an inline APP-SWI-U32 interaction
  Term x = ... pop app arg from the stack ...
  switch (term_tag(x)) {
    case U32: {
      switch (term_val(x)) {
        case 0: {
          ...
        }
        default: {
          // perform an inline APP-LAM interaction
          Term p = ... pop app arg from the stack ...
          ...
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

That function just pops applications from the top-level stack, and consumes
them, performing "inline interactions", and returning only the final result. To
be more specific, every top-level definition that is formatted as a "case-tree";
that is, a tree of λ's and λ-matches, with possibly interleaved local
definitions (LET's) and duplications (DUP's), with each branch head ("tail
position") being an expression composed of applications, operations and
recursive calls; SHOULD be compiled to the equivalent C native function, bailing
out only when interaction net specific interactions (ex: pattern-matching when
the argument of the top stack frame APP is a SUP node, or when the top stack
frame is a DUP instead of an APP, and similar C-incompatible cases).

